# PIV gate

For any task touching 2 or more files, run the PIV loop — see `docs/2. ai-workflows/agentic-coding.md`:

1. **Plan** — use the specs.md planner (`/specsmd-fire-planner`, default FIRE). Before writing the plan: assess complexity, then ask **5 / 10 / 20** multiple-choice questions (4 options each) and recommend one answer per question; wait for confirmation. Before proposing new code: check **library** (worth adopting?) → **in-repo reuse** → **build from scratch**; document the choice in the execution plan. The written plan must include: execution plan, **acceptance criteria**, **validation layer** (for critic/tester), **test flows** (user-facing steps), and commit plan. Present the plan and wait for confirmation before implementing.
2. **Implementation** — use the specs.md builder (`/specsmd-fire-builder`) to execute one work item at a time; small atomic commits.
3. **Validation** — run the [critic](docs/8.%20agents/critic/) agent (adversarial review of plan + implementation), then the [tester](docs/8.%20agents/tester/) agent (execute the Plan's test flows) in a **new chat** with a **different model** than Plan or Implementation. See [validation-layer.md](docs/2.%20ai-workflows/validation-layer.md). Loop back to Implementation on fixable failures, or to Plan on a misunderstanding.
4. **PR review** — only after Validation passes, run the [pr-reviewer](docs/8.%20agents/pr-reviewer/) agent as the final gate. A surprise at PR review means the Validation layer missed something.

Do not write code before the Plan is confirmed. If the task is ambiguous, ask one clarifying question before planning.

Single-file tasks and typo/config fixes are exempt.
